[For a map of Argentina showing the province of La Pampa, go to http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/argentina_pol96.jpg. The province is to the immediate west of Buenos Aires province and its western border abuts the hill country of the Andes foothills. For the departments of Loventue and Toay, go to https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Departamento_Loventu%C3%A9 and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toay_Department. They are adjoining departments in La Pampa province.

Unfortunately, however much one fosters annual vaccination in areas of significant anthrax risk, some ranchers will put it off and then their procrastination becomes public when their animals succumb to this disease. But the only way to rid a region of anthrax is regular vaccination so that remaining spores in the soil can die and not be replaced by blood spillage from new cases. In spite of the literature, anthrax spores are not immortal and in spite of any regeneration will eventually die off. It takes anything from 3 to 8 years, plus there is a natural loss of phages so that remaining spores are apathogenic. Effective anthrax control equals anthrax eradication. Our thanks to Mahmoud and Ramon for their valuable contributions and comments. - Mod.MHJ

HealthMap/ProMED map of La Pampa, Argentina: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8699726,57732]
